The paper deals with decision-making in committees, which is a topic that falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT). The use of different aggregation methods such as Borda count and Copeland rule suggests that the paper may also be relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and data structures (cs.DS). The investigation of how preferences vary and how this affects outcomes suggests that the paper may also be relevant to social and information networks (cs.SI) and machine learning (cs.LG).
